As both offices and schools go remote, working parents’ balancing act has become even more difficult.
And that presents opportunities for employers and employees to rethink their perceptions about working parents, and possibly identify longer-term shifts that could benefit all.
She thinks it’s too early to tell what impact the COVID-19 crisis will have on perceptions of working parents.
And that was all before most parents lost their child care amid the coronavirus crisis – child care that, even in “normal” times, is often excessively expensive.
In every U.S. state, the cost of infant and toddler child care exceeds the federal definition of “affordable,” according to the Center for American Progress.